Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C.

Trim the @Pak Choi{1}, then thinly slice widthways.

Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Roughly chop the @Coriander{1}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Trim the @Cucumber{1/2}, then quarter lengthways. Chop widthways into small pieces.

Roughly chop the @Salted Peanuts{25}.

Pour the cold @Water for the Rice{300} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @Jasmine Rice{150} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil on medium-high heat. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, pop a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil). Once hot, lay the @Duck Breasts{2} in the pan, skin-side down, and fry until the skin is golden, ~{6-8%minutes}. Flip, then sear the other side for ~{1%minute} more.

Transfer to a #baking tray{}, skin-side up, and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until cooked, ~{14-16%minutes}.

Once cooked, transfer to a #plate{}. Cover and rest for ~{10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw duck and its packaging. The duck is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

While the duck roasts, pop the cucumber into a #large bowl{}.

Add the @Rice Vinegar{15}, @Sugar{2} and @Olive Oil{1} and a pinch of @salt{pinch}.

Stir in half the coriander and then set aside.

When the duck is resting, wipe out the frying pan and pop it on high heat with a drizzle of @olive oil{}.

When hot, add the pak choi and stir-fry for ~{2-3%minutes}, then add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Transfer the pak choi to a plate, then reduce the heat to medium.

Add the @Soy Sauce{25} and @Honey{30} to the pan. Bubble away until reduced by two thirds, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> TIP: If your honey has hardened, pop it in a bowl of hot water for 1 min.

Remove from the heat, then return the rested duck to the pan and coat it in the glaze.

Fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir in the remaining coriander, then share between your plates and top with pak choi.

Cut the glazed duck widthways into 1cm slices and serve alongside with the remaining glaze from the pan drizzled over.

Add the cucumber salsa, then scatter with chopped peanuts to finish. Enjoy!